          "id": "rc-l05-c1",
          "title": "CHAPTER 3 The Fragile Fortress “Growing big is the best way",
          "content": "In Chapter 3, we will explore the concept of 'The Fragile Fortress' as it relates to the banking system in China. This idea is illustrated by a quote from Xiao Gang, who was the Chairman of the Bank of China. He pointed out that many believe that growing larger is the best way for banks to increase their profits. However, this strategy does not necessarily ensure that the banking sector will develop sustainably over the long term. Additionally, it does not help create a balanced economic and social structure within the country. The situation is quite complex, and finding effective solutions will require careful thought and planning.\nTo understand this better, we will look back at the Asian Financial Crisis of 1997. This crisis was a major event that threatened the stability of financial institutions in China. During this challenging time, Zhu Rongji, who was a key leader, gathered a group of reformers to come up with a plan to address the issues facing the banks. One of the immediate actions taken to restore confidence in the banking system was the Ministry of Finance (MOF) injecting new capital into the banks in 1998. This move was crucial in helping to stabilize the financial system and regain trust among the public and investors.\nAs we delve into this chapter, we will analyze the implications of these actions and discuss how they shaped the future of banking in China. We will also consider the lessons learned from this period and how they can inform current and future banking practices. Understanding these dynamics is essential for grasping the broader economic landscape in China and the challenges that lie ahead for its financial institutions.\nContext recap: In Chapter 3, we will explore the concept of 'The Fragile Fortress' as it relates to the banking system in China. This idea is illustrated by a quote from Xiao Gang, who was the Chairman of the Bank of China. He pointed out that many believe that growing larger is the best way for banks to increase their profits. However, this strategy does not necessarily ensure that the banking sector will develop sustainably over the long term.\nWhy this matters: CHAPTER 3 The Fragile Fortress “Growing big is the best way helps learners in Economics/China connect ideas from Red Capitalism to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
